'}, {'created': '2015-11-28 22:20:10.000000000', 'message': "HyperV: remove driver from the neutron tree

The hyperv drivers and code should be part of the networking-hyperv
project (https://github.com/openstack/networking-hyperv).

A few changes are necessary in order to prevent Hyper-V deployments from
breaking, especially when upgrading to Mitaka.

First of all, instead of the current Hyper-V mechanism_driver, the
networking_hyperv equivalent must be used.
Secondly, Hyper-V deployments are configured to use the in-branch
HyperVSecurityGroupsDriver. Removing it will cause the Hyper-V
Neutron Agent to fail. If the agent is configured to use the old driver, the
networking_hyperv's driver must be used instead and the users must be warned to
update their configuration files to use the networking_hyperv's security groups
driver.

Removes the neutron-hyperv-agent entry point from setup.cfg.
Replaces the Hyper-V mechanism_driver in setup.cfg with the
networking_hyperv equivalent.
Removes neutron.plugins.hyperv.agent.security_groups_driver.HyperVSecurityGroupsDriver.
Adds map between old firewall drivers and their replacement in securitygroups_rpc.
Adds logic that detects misconfigured firewall_drivers, logs a warning and replaces
them with proper drivers.

Co-Authored-By: Claudiu Belu <cbelu@cloudbasesolutions.com>

Depends-On: I3a25f18b4f3a0621cb92b44eb61e434fa87e0aab

Change-Id: I32451cba6933e88306a4308a07f3f0d1b81f626c
Closes-bug: #1520054
"}, {'created': '2015-11-28 22:28:32.000000000', 'message': "HyperV: remove driver from the neutron tree

project (https://github.com/openstack/networking-hyperv).

A few changes are necessary in order to prevent Hyper-V deployments from
breaking, especially when upgrading to Mitaka.

First of all, instead of the current Hyper-V mechanism_driver, the
networking_hyperv equivalent must be used.
Secondly, Hyper-V deployments are configured to use the in-branch
HyperVSecurityGroupsDriver. Removing it will cause the Hyper-V
Neutron Agent to fail. If the agent is configured to use the old driver, the
networking_hyperv's driver must be used instead and the users must be warned to
update their configuration files to use the networking_hyperv's security groups
driver.

Removes the neutron-hyperv-agent entry point from setup.cfg.
Replaces the Hyper-V mechanism_driver in setup.cfg with the
networking_hyperv equivalent.
Removes neutron.plugins.hyperv.agent.security_groups_driver.HyperVSecurityGroupsDriver.
Adds map between old firewall drivers and their replacement in securitygroups_rpc.

commit_message:
Hyper-V: remove driver from the neutron tree

The hyperv drivers and code should be part of the networking-hyperv
project (https://github.com/openstack/networking-hyperv).

A few changes are necessary in order to prevent Hyper-V deployments from
breaking, especially when upgrading to Mitaka.

Hyper-V deployments are configured to use the in-branch HyperVSecurityGroupsDriver.
Removing it will cause the Hyper-V Neutron Agent to fail. If the agent is
configured to use the old driver, the networking_hyperv's driver must be used
instead and the users must be warned to update their configuration files to
use the networking_hyperv's security groups driver.

Removes the neutron-hyperv-agent entry point from setup.cfg.
Removes the hyperv mechanism_driver from setup.cfg
Moves the in-tree HyperVSecurityGroupsDriver to the networking_hyperv equivalent.
Logs a warning if the in-tree HyperVSecurityGroupsDriver is used.
Removes pywin32 and wmi requirements, as they've been included in networking_hyperv
and they are Hyper-V specific requirements.
Adds release note regarding the deprecated security groups driver.

Co-Authored-By: Claudiu Belu <cbelu@cloudbasesolutions.com>

Depends-On: I3a25f18b4f3a0621cb92b44eb61e434fa87e0aab

Change-Id: I32451cba6933e88306a4308a07f3f0d1b81f626c
Closes-bug: #1520054

commit_message:
Fix api_server agent test that broke due to a dep change

The test was slightly incorrect to begin with, but the issue didn't
become apparent until the oslo.log update from 1.13.0 to 2.0.0 for
whatever reason. open() raises IOError() not Exception() so it was not
being handled properly.

Also taking this opportunity to standardize the use of builtins to
match our other tests.

(cherry picked from commit Idab637b09e8a437333f810f82f45b3e9c027dfdd)

Change-Id: Iddafa6636777aac83e9e5b030466ded46170c52c

commit_message:
Enable vhost-user ports on supported platforms.

Over the past six months ovs and odl have been extended to report
the supported port types available on the vswitch.
This change extends the bind_port implementation to consult the supported
port types of the vswitch on the selected compute host when selecting the
VIF_TYPE to bind.

Change-Id: Ib97c2d2e1e2e1cd536bc27ac54a8f27a5963e883
Closes-Bug: #1477611
Depends-On: I78cac4f5b9de381ebb7c5a97a34f60ebe6e56ba3

commit_message:
Extract loadbalancer_id from listener create events

We're currently dropping the lb id from listener events, causing
a cache lookup that ends up hitting deleted loadbalancers instead
of the intended one.  This fixes it and looks for loadbalancer_id
in the correct place of listener create events body.

Closes-bug: #1509595
(cherry picked from commit 1ef5c523e98eaf8d90184083d8f4af4f2619b527)

Change-Id: I541a2132d66cb0c737fd25452afd87950828ea43

commit_message:
Fix Resource.__eq__ mismatch semantics of object equal

The __eq__ of apiclient.base.Resource will return True,
if the two objects have same id, even if they have different
other attributes value. The behavior is weird and don't
match the semantics of object equal. The objects that have
different value should be different objects.
Fix this issue and add some test cases in this patch.

Change-Id: I24ba39bf90d727116f256de46241746520efbfee
Closes-Bug: #1499369

If an error occurs in nova.cmd.baseproxy the method exit_with_error
will be executed that looks as follows:

def exit_with_error(msg, errno=-1):

commit_message:
Fix error handling in nova.cmd.baseproxy

If an error occurs in nova.cmd.baseproxy the method exit_with_error
will be executed that looks as follows:

def exit_with_error(msg, errno=-1):
	print(msg) and sys.exit(errno)

However, in python2.7 this method terminates the application without
printing anything(unable to flush on time) and in Python3.4 it does
strange things because print() returns None.

This commit modifies exit_with_error method to output error message
with stderr(which in unbuffered).

Change-Id: I519b68f8c2bc62988de87bdd2847d5f3be7e532d
Closes-Bug: #1506213

commit_message:
Avoid the dual-naming confusion

The module 'driver' is an import and it is also a variable name,
this can be confusing so rename it to be named differently.

TrivialFix

Change-Id: Ie45dd6901afdd7083a75adf75f73e99bfe304ab5

Remove duplicated profiles section from bandit.yaml

commit_message:
Enables py3 unit tests for libvirt.host module

Python 3  '/' returns a float, while '//' returns an int.

Removes unit tests from tests-py3.txt blacklist.

Partially implements blueprint: nova-python3-mitaka

Change-Id: I87338aac1871a63dc17f1b81a7870d8911f3a399

We added a warning message about the v2 ES client not working
with searchlight. This works fine, but a complete devstack
run wasn't tested. When I just stacked, it couldn't complete
because of using sys.exit(1) when the warning is emitted.
This changes it to (0) so that devstack will, well, err...
stack.

Once global requirements and searchlight requirements
are capped at v2, the exit code of 1 will be more appropriate.

commit_message:
Elasticsearch v2 client warning causes devstack to not stack

We added a warning message about the v2 ES client not working
with searchlight. This works fine, but a complete devstack
run wasn't tested. When I just stacked, it couldn't complete
because of using sys.exit(1) when the warning is emitted.
This changes it to (0) so that devstack will, well, err...
stack.

Once global requirements and searchlight requirements
are capped at v2, the exit code of 1 will be more appropriate.

Change-Id: I92bde9826ef789c390b4abc791cb384aef4d422b
Partial-Bug: #253177

commit_message:
Ajax errors should return correctly.

Currently, any ajax call that hits an error other than NotAuthorized or
NotAuthenticated the end-response returned will likely be a 500 error
with all the html of our ISE page included.

Richard Jones's API code already provides a way to handle these issues,
so we should use that!

Co-Authored-By: Matt Borland <matt.borland@hpe.com>

Change-Id: I53a65d6590c6005dff96d583b2c55a0653b2b1c9
Closes-Bug: #1489905

commit_message:
Remove 'MANIFEST.in'

Everything in this file is automatically generated by pbr. There
appears to be no good reason to keep it around.
More details please see:
https://github.com/openstack-dev/pbr/blob/master/pbr/packaging.py#L384

Change-Id: I0b802106c9b1fe95840de3605042c45330627486

commit_message:
Additional inspection role and adding role to NV job script

Addition of an inspection role, the appropriate test and enrollment
playbooks, and an entry for the node inspection to take place as
part of the long running non-voting job for initial testing.

Implements: blueprint bifrost-inspector-support
Depends-On: I4ba3f0cf4ad6f5466e52f5d034bb217f06eec7dd
Change-Id: Iceaf96aaeedc99530fabe2af47bab414d689c3dd

I don't understand why this patch set is required.

In Arvind's patch - https://review.openstack.org/#/c/222409/ a change is made to setup.cfg to have the stevedore entry point for the ML2 ODL driver point to the new refactord driver.
If someone wants to use the original driver they just need to edit that file and have "opendaylight" point to the old location/class entry point.
If preferred you can add a comment to Arvind's patch set to keep "opendaylight" pointing to the original driver and add a new entry point "opendaylightv2" pointing to the refactored driver. The changes to devstack are not required.

I would hope that by the end of the M-release that the new driver has been fully tested and verified to work under all existing ODL conditions and the setup.cfg will be changed to only have one variable, "opendaylight", pointing to the refactored driver. (We can keep the original (now deprecated) driver and UT code around for a release or two.)'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-12 21:18:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

commit_message:
Avoid Pool object creating in pool_member functional calls

This patch revises pool_member related function calls to invoke
get_id method to get target pool ID. This change avoids Pool
object creating which is unnecessary.

Change-Id: Ie1150040b9178f5b18ca1de6ab141478f73140cf

commit_message:
Add authorize method to Connection

The ability to know your application is going to fail due to a
credential issue *before* getting into the application and attempting to
make some API call can be useful. This change adds Connection.authorize,
which just does the same thing we do implicitly. It's entirely optional
and is documented as such.

Co-Authored-By: Qiming Teng (tengqim@cn.ibm.com)
Closes-Bug: #1513200
Change-Id: If86f308da909c4ff31f37294a000c6972c947182

In I7cf94a1b2cbbfe67282e8a157548caff825d2811, we we moved
type formatting from generator to type, however we still have
some older code/libraries that were using a Opt with a type
set to a string. We need to support them until we fix and
fix all use cases. So we explicitly check if format_defaults
is present and call it if it is. If format_defaults is
not present we call the older code from the change id
mentioned above.

Change-Id: I298e75afbd43bd35aba93c38129008789ed39146

commit_message:
[fix-compat] Support older use case for Opt type

In I7cf94a1b2cbbfe67282e8a157548caff825d2811, we we moved
type formatting from generator to type, however we still have
some older code/libraries that were using a Opt with a type
set to a string. We need to support them until we find and
fix all use cases. So we explicitly check if format_defaults
is present and call it if it is. If format_defaults is
not present we call the older code from the change id
mentioned above.

Closes-Bug: #1522637
Change-Id: I298e75afbd43bd35aba93c38129008789ed39146

commit_message:
Creating nova-secret with safe file permissions

This fix will make sure that the nova-secret file will
be created with save "0600" (r--) permissions.

Additionally a new task will make sure that the file is removed
from the filesystem. This will minimize any unprivileged exposure
to the nova-secret file content.

Change-Id: I1c3ec322b2a661cf7dce0334866c90201bbef0a0
Closes-Bug: #1519088
(cherry picked from commit eca0f5ddfba5ac12fc0199d854b3f18504f9ccd3)

commit_message:
akanda->astara 1st step: Remove namespace package, add symlink

Moves the namespace package to top-level akanda_neutron and adds
a symlink shim to preserve history.

Change-Id: I4b62a9f43bbc5d44628bb27851156ac77e2ce5eb
Partially-Implements: blueprint convert-to-astara

updating, too.

commit_message:
Remove low-level PyKMIP test asserts

This change removes two low-level asserts that test the internals of
PyKMIP core. The referenced portions of PyKMIP have been modified in the
latest release. Once the latest release has been published, these asserts
will be added back in, modified to work properly with the new version of
PyKMIP.

Partial-Bug: #1522856
Change-Id: I50b9a4ad935d6458c5dc42f8184a724c78a28a59

commit_message:
Add CLI option guideline

A lot of changes have been proposed to add options to
*-create/update operations. This guideline tries to clarify
the conventions used in neutornclient.

Change-Id: I2c66c3dcba2569fdac2e54afb49406084cbf7037

What if they live in the config reference guide?'}, {'account_id': 7715, 'date': '2015-12-01 05:49:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

This patch isn't ready until dependent patch is merged. We also should hear Tom's suggestion and get Ops consensus."}, {'account_id': 9551, 'date': '2015-12-01 09:38:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hi Tom,

You make a valid point that operators like to have sample configuration files per project. That is why in the release notes we specify the means to generate these sample config files: "use tools/generate_config_file_samples.sh to generate them." 

This therefore means that anyone can get sample config files as per the latest code without the unnecessary overhead of keeping a static version of the config file in the repository. This also removes the overhead of to developers having to add duplicate changes in these static config files and in some cases code and config files are not in sync.

I have also looked at some of the other projects and from what I can tell the following projects do not keep static config files in their repos: Ceilometer, Heat, Keystone and Nova.

Do you think this is a viable solution to all groups or have you a better alternative?

Thanks,
Martin'}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-12-01 17:18:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Tom, I don't believe that request is reasonable. We provide a script to generate the files, we document how to use it; we free developers from maintaining the file. I don't believe huge dev pain is justified here only because ops are not willing to execute a script to get the files.

As for docs, we will plan to post configuration options to docs. website after we are done with that cleanup in all neutron repos."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-12-03 15:04:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

Starting gate jobs.
http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 8124, 'date': '2015-12-03 15:28:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Ihar, @Zigo, do you know if packagers will continue to distribute neutron packages with config sample files?'}, {'account_id': 9515, 'date': '2015-12-03 15:31:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Cedric,

They should, otherwise we see tons of complaints in the various support channels, particularly involving the installation guide.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-12-03 21:13:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+2

- gate-tempest-dsvm-neutron-large-ops http://logs.openstack.org/48/251348/1/gate/gate-tempest-dsvm-neutron-large-ops/c017908/ : SUCCESS in 32m 19s'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-12-03 21:13:32.000000000', 'content': 'Change has been successfully merged into the git repository.'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-12-04 01:03:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Keeping sample files in tree leads to human errors. It's a painful process to deal with regardless of the hat you're wearing, ops or otherwise: in the former you may be looking at a file that doesn't match code capability, in the latter, you gotta remember not to leave things behind.

Best thing to do is to educate people to run the config generation script and be happy with it."}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-12-04 07:45:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hi,

"Running the script" is not an education issue.

The merging of this patch is another step back from supporting what ops need and want.'}, {'account_id': 6476, 'date': '2015-12-04 13:28:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Tom, this has been discussed MANY times. Any generated configuration which contains Oslo libraries content CANNOT be stored in the Git, because it is by definition WRONG (since it depends on the version of the Oslo library which it was used to build with). So we MUST NOT keep wrong configuration files within our Git repositories, even if this is less convenient.

It is up to package distribution maintainers to provide config files which are matching whatever Oslo lib version is in the distribution.

Could we please stop discussing this, as we came to the consensus, with this technical point of argumentation which has never been contested?'}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-12-04 15:16:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Reverted

This patchset was reverted in change: Ia94ddae9c7c2bdd39584d102b0a471205c2dc77c'}, {'account_id': 9551, 'date': '2015-12-04 21:20:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Revert of patch was abandoned. The issue was solved in change Ia6d3f0d789fad30d451a138b4ed0ff162ba0b00e.

The issue in this patch broken the gate requirements job. A test has been added to prevent this from happening in future.'}]

commit_message:
Remove Neutron core static example configuration files

Oslo config generator was introduced in patch [1] to
automatically generate the sample Neutron core configuration
files.

This patch removes the static example configuration files from
the repository as they are now redundant.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/204206/

DocImpact

Change-Id: Ic7ae2e038b5bd7b215c65c9c565bfe31ef551520
Partially-Implements: blueprint autogen-neutron-conf-file
Closes-bug: #1199963
Depends-On: Ic37a16b6cf8eb92030649f1fc8b198738a8cc104

subject: Database agnostic implementation
messages:
[{'account_id': 19491, 'date': '2015-12-02 10:02:53.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 10068, 'date': '2015-12-02 10:03:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html
    Commit Messages: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-12-02 10:10:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

Build failed (check pipeline).  For information on how to proceed, see http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html#automated-testing

- gate-monasca-common-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/02/252302/1/check/gate-monasca-common-pep8/945d237/ : FAILURE in 46s
- gate-monasca-common-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/02/252302/1/check/gate-monasca-common-python27/16b4e13/ : SUCCESS in 52s
- gate-monasca-common-build http://logs.openstack.org/02/252302/1/check/gate-monasca-common-build/140c789/ : SUCCESS in 3m 18s'}, {'account_id': 19491, 'date': '2015-12-02 10:17:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Commit message was updated'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-12-02 10:24:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

Build failed (check pipeline).  For information on how to proceed, see http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html#automated-testing

- gate-monasca-common-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/02/252302/2/check/gate-monasca-common-pep8/2635879/ : FAILURE in 45s
- gate-monasca-common-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/02/252302/2/check/gate-monasca-common-python27/396cf47/ : SUCCESS in 1m 59s
- gate-monasca-common-build http://logs.openstack.org/02/252302/2/check/gate-monasca-common-build/cce489c/ : SUCCESS in 3m 35s'}, {'account_id': 16222, 'date': '2015-12-02 12:15:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

What is the incentive to replace hibernate with jOOQ? Does it solve any issues?'}, {'account_id': 7052, 'date': '2015-12-02 15:26:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I would like to understand the motivation of this change.
Can you please create a spec of a wiki where you describe the need and benefits of this change?'}, {'account_id': 8126, 'date': '2015-12-02 15:27:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Same comment as fabio, please provide blueprint/spec describing change/motivation.'}, {'account_id': 19491, 'date': '2015-12-02 15:59:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I don't know hot to make blueprint. I only observed that in your code was two implementations of connection to database (raw mysql and hibernate). Also I saw that fixes was added only to raw mysql part. I believe that hibernate could have some performance issue or something (I'm not sure what cause is connected that you have still mysql and hibernate). But I think that it is good to have support to many databases. And I believe that jOQQ is better for this goal than hibernate. In jOQQ you could create almost every query like as in raw connection, but in jOQQ is possible to write one query which should work on several databases. If you don't want this code it's ok for me, but in monasca-api I added also similar solution for python part."}, {'account_id': 19491, 'date': '2015-12-03 10:14:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Commit message was updated'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-12-03 10:25:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-monasca-common-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/02/252302/3/check/gate-monasca-common-pep8/2ff8369/ : SUCCESS in 48s
- gate-monasca-common-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/02/252302/3/check/gate-monasca-common-python27/670d9a6/ : SUCCESS in 48s
- gate-monasca-common-build http://logs.openstack.org/02/252302/3/check/gate-monasca-common-build/dc6a1db/ : SUCCESS in 3m 15s'}, {'account_id': 7052, 'date': '2015-12-03 17:26:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-2

oiskam, I am not in favor to support this tool mainly because does not have a sustainable community and it is not clear where the performance benefit lies.
If you look at this link:
https://github.com/jOOQ/jOOQ/graphs/contributors
Only the company founder is making the contributions whereas Hibernate is a well established open source project.'}, {'account_id': 19491, 'date': '2015-12-03 17:43:01.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

useless code'}, {'account_id': 19491, 'date': '2015-12-03 17:59:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

It's ok for me. I hoped that I could make some contribution.
You can check https://review.openstack.org/#/c/252305/ there was a code for orm in python. Probably another portion of useless code for you, but if you want you can do with it anything. I don't have much free time to separate it and for trying push it in a new change.

And I can't agree with you that jOOQ is useless. In my opinion is for another goals. With jOOQ you can focus on database and create almost every query for this database.
So you can start from schema in database and later create queries in java.

With hibernate the best solution is starting from model in java for hibernate. And later generate and create schema in database.

I agree that often hibernate is playing good. But in your case I saw that hibernate layer was created later and for example for group_concate there is some workaround.

Additionally if hibernate is good you should consider to support it at 100% and abandon probably part with raw mysql queries.


Bye.

I really thank you for your time."}, {'account_id': 7052, 'date': '2015-12-03 22:03:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

For the records, I never said that this code was useless. I said that this library does not seem to have a lot of community support and that is my major concern. We cannot adopt a library that in few months may not be supported anymore.'}, {'account_id': 16222, 'date': '2015-12-04 08:01:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I think we could still consider the sqlalchemy part.'}, {'account_id': 19491, 'date': '2015-12-04 20:55:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@fabio for the records. The idea of open source is if you find some interesting library or program and it fits good for your needs than you can support it too yourself. And became a new contributor for this project :). But it's only my private opinion. For this reason I wanted contribute to your project. I found it interesting for me and I wanted to contribute to monasca world.

And I will repeat I don't say that you have to take jOOQ stuff. The more important is that in your code are two implementations and you should choose one. If I were you I would choose hibernate.

But it's only my opinion.

@witold if you are interested with sqlalchemy part take it and push change. I don't have now enough free time. And I haven't tested this part in temptest or production.

bye
bye"}]

commit_message:
Do not include reno releasenotes in normal documentation

Per the recent release note guidelines for libraries [1],
reno based release notes will be moved out from the normal docs.
The previous (partial) release notes are also moved to
releasenotes directory. The developer documentation now
has a link to the releasenote web site.

In addition, having reno directive in normal sphinx document
prevents users from generating our docs from release tarballs.

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-November/080694.html

Change-Id: I817f1a7331b8664486544c82e1a9a917864601bf
Closes-Bug: #1520096

Lin, Guang: So I feel kind of stuck here.  I originally proposed a separate API for domain specific roles (if you lack back at the earlier patches), but the feedback was: go work with ayoung to integrate this with implied roles (because it IS an implied role.....just not used in the same way).  So I have done that!

Now the kicker, I think, could actually be WHO will be creating and managing the two sorts of implied role (and hence what does the policy file look like for the API protection). The domain admin MUST be able to set up a domain specific role and the mapping to the underlying global policy roles without any help from the cloud admin (who would typically set up the global implied roles).'}, {'account_id': 1941, 'date': '2015-12-02 14:34:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 28:

(4 comments)

Henry: yeah, if we re-use the same API endpoint how do we configure the policy to only allow Domain Admin to create the Domain specific role. I don't think its possible with our policy engine.

If you can make it work, I am fine with this."}, {'account_id': 1941, 'date': '2015-12-02 14:34:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 28: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 10046, 'date': '2015-12-02 18:10:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 28: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 6460, 'date': '2015-12-02 20:21:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 28: Code-Review+2

(1 comment)

So we really have put henry-nash between a rock and a hard spot on this.  He is getting feedback to go in two different directions.   My guess is we just don't know enough about which direction is really the best way to go yet.  My recommendation is we should be minimalist and agile.  What if we let henry-nash see if he can make this work by reusing implied roles.  If that does not work or the user experience is dreadful and confusing he can always fallback to providing a separate API.  I think if we let him get going on this we will get code to evaluate and that will give us the clarity we need without us suffering from "analysis paralysis" which is what is kind of happening now.'}, {'account_id': 5707, 'date': '2015-12-02 21:33:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 28:

Lin, Guang - so looking at how the API protection would work, I think this is OK with with the implied roles API (i.e. create_implied_role rule would allow a domain admin to add an inference if the prior role ID was a domain specific role....but if you were cloud admin you could manipulate non-domain-specific implies roles).

Seems like your key issue is whether we need a specific API....i.e. something like a domain specific role-group, that a domain admin could create?  Then the issue is - do we duplicate all the assignment APIs, to take either a global role or a domain specific role group? If you don't do that (and say that a role group is really a special type of role)...then I don't think it is that different than re-using implied roles. So I think what we are doing does make sense."}, {'account_id': 5707, 'date': '2015-12-02 21:38:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 28:

The policy rule would look something like this:

"identity:create_implied_role": "(role:admin and domain_id:%(target.prior_role_id.domain_id)s) or rule:cloud_admin"'}, {'account_id': 1916, 'date': '2015-12-02 21:46:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 28:

Henry, so I got stuck on the implied roles are in the token response while the domain-specific roles are not part. That's a rather big UX gap there. Domain-specific roles are a lot like user groups. They are transience (hope I am using the right word here) if you will. They are not part of token response. Implied roles, on the other hand, are something different. They are not transience, they are really just "roles". So in that regard, they are fundamentally different because they behave differently.

All I am asking is to please consider your users. Create something that doesn't make their head hurt. Create something that is easy for them understand and use. And I just don't think overloading the implied role APIs would make it easier on the end users.

Look, like I said many times, I am totally for the idea of domain-specific roles. We need that. But can we please make it a bit more usable?'}, {'account_id': 5707, 'date': '2015-12-02 22:04:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 28:

Understand the point you are making.  But to be completely accurate, the implied roles ALWAYS go in the token...it's the prior_roles that don't go in the token, in the case of domain specific roles. (I'd be OK with the restriction, for instance, of saying you can only have one level of domains-specific role inference - i.e. one domain specific role cannot imply another domain specific role - which would be the case of simple role groups that operated like user groups). The alternative is:

1) Create a concept of domain specific role groups, with the associated API to add/remove roles
2) Duplicate the assignment APIs to allow versions that accept a domain specific role group instead of a normal role
3) Expand the assignment table to store these different assignments, and extend the list assignment API to handle all the role-group ways of getting roles in addition to the implied-roles way of getting roles.

Clearer? Maybe? More to learn? Sure. I'm just not convinced the issue is serious enough to justify this additional level abstraction."}, {'account_id': 1916, 'date': '2015-12-02 22:24:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 28:

Henry, the way I understood the implied roles spec, both the prior and implied roles goes into token response, which make sense for its purpose.

"Both explicitly assigned and implied roles will be included in the token validation response. With the above example, if a user was explicitly assigned the role editor on a project, the validation of a token for that user and scoped to the project would have the roles: editor and reader included in the response."

As for your options, I really like option 1), which is to create a domain-specific role groups and the corresponding APIs to manipulate them. That would be consistent with the rest of the APIs (i.e. user groups).'}, {'account_id': 5707, 'date': '2015-12-02 22:57:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 28:

I was making the clarification that it is the prior role that is handled differently between domain specific roles and regular one, not the implied roles.  Further, the rule is a domain specific role (i.e. one where you provide a domain id when you create the role) never goes in a token.  Full stop. Not sure there is any confusion there.

As to my "options" - those aren't options...my point is you have to do ALL those things to get a working API, not just 1).'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-12-03 06:36:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 28: Verified-1

commit_message:
Domain Specific Roles

This spec outlines support for domain specific roles that can be
used with the implied roles functionality to allow a domain
administrator to better model their role usage.

Implements: blueprint domain-specific-roles

Change-Id: I2aa390edca32734857e5f3cc8decacf4072e697a

commit_message:
Disable CentOS6 nodes in nodepool

We now have no more jobs using CentOS6, so disable them in nodepool.

-1 is magic value for: Do not even build new images.

Change-Id: I573a2709389c66780a822325b882609e853b8b84

Unfortunately, the conversion to use the catalog is not as small/easy a fix as addressing the current pattern.

While I agree that the use of the catalog is a much better fix, due to the way Xen Plugin works, and the scattering of code around the code base that assumes host/port/version/use_ssl is passed the "correct" fix is a much larger/further reaching changeset.

I am going to argue that the aforementioned correct fix is perfect being the enemy of good.

commit_message:
Don't drop uri path when selecting glance api

Do not drop the glance URI path when selecting the glance api server.

urlparse.urlparse splits out the path from the host/port/etc and we
previously just dropped the path on the floor. This means that it is
impossible from Nova's perspective to have glance located anywhere but
the root of the server/vhost/etc that glance is acting on.

Closes-Bug #1520937

Change-Id: Ib037ef20b6f3a803ca597f1571c66c7373af3dbf

Nice point, Andrew.'}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2015-12-03 16:32:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Andrew & @Ken,

I'm trying to figure out how to approach fixing the problem I'm running up against. Right now I am up against an issue where glance cannot be any place but "/" for the server it is on. This is because nova has no way to use URI paths. 

this code just digs us deeper into this pit. I'm being told that the acceptable fix for the uri thing is to use the catalog, but that is a massive change. So, please advise, how should we fix this? Take the cost of adding to the current mechanisms nova uses (pretty easy actually) and work on the catalog bit later?

It is very difficult to contribute fixes with the direction from the nova team being at odds between the patchsets.'}, {'account_id': 5441, 'date': '2015-12-03 17:02:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'm not really clear on where exactly you're hitting an issue with URI paths but looking at this code I would expect it's related to the endpoint, right?  Is there anything specific to the method in this patch that's an issue?

I don't have an issue with working to fix the current code to do what you're trying to do and address the service catalog later.  But I certainly understand the desire to not add more cruft in this area since it is currently a poorly crafted mess."}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2015-12-04 20:41:27.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Remove unused glance function and tests

As part of the effort to discover the glance endpoint via the service
catalog, this removes unused code from the glance file. This change
is to ensure that we are not keeping code around that could produce
the wrong values.

Change-Id: Id3cff0f0a86952860c1d4b7f3670bd0c786b7066
Related-Bug: #1520937
Partial-Bug: #1084138

commit_message:
Added to ability to set mtu for lxcbr0

The lxc_host role overrides the configuration
done by the system administrator on the host.

If mtu was defined in /etc/lxc/ and in the
system network interfaces, then these configurations
will be overriden.

This commit should allow the deployer to set the
mtu for its lxcbr0 network, by setting the variable
lxc_net_mtu.

Fixes-Bug: #1518303

(cherry-picked from I42ab3d0a2c20ae94335de195cdb14579d9f59f5f)

Change-Id: Ibdfe6f40199ecec764ca18b2155d37bf52cf2ba8

commit_message:
Fix nova_virt_type auto-detection

In https://review.openstack.org/243098 nova_virt_type auto-detection
was implemented, but the default nova_virt_type value of kvm was left
in place, resulting in the auto-detection never happening.

This patch implements the auto-detection if nova-virt_type is not set
and removes the default value for nova-virt_type.

Change-Id: Ic1c8f042bc6bbee542373d335f338866efa06dc7
(cherry picked from commit 5e54fd379edd856879e6261cea22ad52556b00dd)

commit_message:
remove gate-devstack-dsvm-cells

gate-devstack-dsvm-cells was a stop gap job on juno/kilo to use
devstack exercises on cells until the tempest job got working. The
tempest job was working in kilo, and now votes.

With juno gone, and the old job almost testing nothing on kilo (it
boots 1 vm only), we should remove it and just leave the tempest-cells
job where it already is.

Change-Id: I829903b0690faea2d499f4ba8a2393cf31ed4601

commit_message:
Updated the py_pkgs lookup plugin for multi source

The py_pkgs lookup plugin will now handle multiple sources. This change
was needed to enable the system to allow for overrides of repo_package
resources and general python packaging as found throughout the stack.
The module has precedence as it loads / searches for packages and he item
loaded last is the one that has the most precedence.

The repo-build play has been updated to now search for compatible packages
in the main playbook directory, the root ansible role directory and the
user_variables file.

Documentation has been added regarding this capability and how to override
and set items to meet the needs of the deployment.

Closes-Bug: #1510575
Implements: blueprint independent-role-repositories
Change-Id: Ib7cda14db18c0ca58bb5ac495d1c201812cf0f48
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>
(cherry picked from commit 2f35e36e54efb7b0e767d0888782f86696ef84b9)

commit_message:
Add sdist check to pep8 build script

Inability to create an sdist tarball is a fundamental problem, but
because of how we run tox in unittest builders, we often do not catch
this anymore. The potential harm is that a change can land to a project
that breaks the ability to create an sdist or run a direct setup.py
install or pip install . - which will in turn break the requirements
gate which tries to do those things.

Change-Id: Ibc36edb06cf072b9f0cf664fae3c3c2273ff71e6

commit_message:
[config-ref] Manila cleanup

Overall:
Follow our conventions for formatting and style.

EMC:
Remove mention that server needs to be restarted.

Generic:
Remove Juno and Liberty changes, this guide documents Mitaka.

HDFS:
Do not duplicate information about options that are in the table.

Change-Id: Ibc4af2d7e16e9baceea33a802a3c147e8a0ee8d8

commit_message:
Fixes playbook runtime issues with ldap

When using an LDAP backend the plabooks fail when "ensuring.*"
which is a keystone client action. The reason for the failure is
related to how ldap backend, and is triggered when the service
users are within the ldap and not SQL. To resolve the issue a boolean
conditional was created on the various OS_.* roles to skip specific
tasks when the service users have already been added into LDAP.

Closes-Bug: #1518351
Closes-Bug: #1519174
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>
(cherry picked from commit 283a89afa8d9d6840f77e902ad1127260f32a195)
Signed-off-by: Matthew Thode <mthode@mthode.org>

Change-Id: I1727d896373cbcf667da779c8dd62145268eb8c2

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-11-21 00:24:24.000000000', 'message': 'Fix repr of a host from a hosts.list()

The os-hosts API uses different attribute names depending on
whether the host was returned as part of a list or not.
A host returned from 'show host' has the attribute "host"
whereas a host returned from 'list hosts' has the attribute
"host_name".

This adds a new resource class HostFromList that derives from Host,
that uses "host_name" as the attribute for the __repr__ string.

Co-Authored-By: Chung Chih, Hung <lyan.h@inwinstack.com>

Closes-Bug: #1434167

commit_message:
Fix repr of a host from a hosts.list()

The os-hosts API uses different attribute names depending on
whether the host was returned as part of a list or not.
A host returned from 'show host' has the attribute "host"
whereas a host returned from 'list hosts' has the attribute
"host_name".

This adds a host_name property to the Host class that will set the
"host" attribute if necessary. Although this doesn't exactly mirror
the responses coming back from nova api, it will make it easier for
users to use the objects interchangeably for hosts.list() operations
and hosts.update() operations, for example.

Co-Authored-By: Chung Chih, Hung <lyan.h@inwinstack.com>

Closes-Bug: #1434167

Change-Id: I5c339bdd1ab867d972759ade9a10b86bfda1e70a

commit_message:
gnocchi: remove possible ending / in URL

If the URL ends up with a /, then URL are built with 2 /
e.g. POST //v1/foobar and that does not work.

Change-Id: I98e9a0e85e9dd6ae022bbc0543244e533b1307f7
(cherry picked from commit 0e776f8f096729d59760f8c5fc8a26e2b34567c4)

commit_message:
create apt_get_update to try to work around broken mirrors

Ubuntu's apt mirroring mechanism produces inconsistent mirrors pretty
regularly. The devstack-gate apt-get update model seems to have been
more effective getting past this than what we did in devstack. Adopt
that method for our updates.

Change-Id: I97c7896ef38b275aacb4f933fc849acee1bab858

commit_message:
Fix postgresql manifest

Remove hardcoded postgresql version and paths, because they broke
installation in CentOS7

Is compatible with CentOS6 master node

Change-Id: Ib094323ddf4d1b45f94e8939c30290ddcc2f7920

commit_message:
Emit warning if indexing with elasticsearch v2

If the v2 client is installed, emit a warning when attempting to index
without --no-delete (the default) instructing the user to consult the
documentation to manually delete the index and rerun with --no-delete.

This can be removed after global-requirements is capped (see
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/252075/) or once reindexing no longer
requires an in-place clearing of data.

Change-Id: I8ad3efb0addf6be516b0f8bbf18543b19175ac5d
Partial-Bug: #1515412

commit_message:
Update for akanda->astara rename

This updates astara-horizon code for the project rename:

* References to Akanda/akanda changed to Astara/astara
* Refernces to RUG/Rug removed or replaced with astara
* RugClient -> AstaraClient
* Panel renamed RUG -> Astara

Also added copyright headers to all code files.

Change-Id: I78eeacda4f8ae16a61890d9cbfd41ddf037b9677
Partially-implements: blueprint astara-horizon-mitaka

commit_message:
Fix incorrect task status with wrong parameter

Now, when use wrong parameter to create a import task, the task's
status will be processing forever. Actually the task has been stopped
and returned error.
So in this situation, the task's status should be changed into failure.

Closes-bug: #1495519
Change-Id: Ie4b3b92aaddcdbb839aadf61c75fc0c915e2040e

commit_message:
Fix metric-statistics doesn't respond "Bad Request"

When metric-statistics with end_time equals start_time received,
python monasca-api responds "200 OK" instead of "400 Bad Request".

Change-Id: I56cf42c2530be83b4555a05b4c433666a4ccdb5e
Closes-Bug: #1520029

commit_message:
Fix bug where clean steps do not run

A bug was introduced during Liberty where Ironic transparently
ignores all clean steps and finishes cleaning. This is caused
by _get_node_next_clean_steps returning an empty list when
cleaning has just started. Fix this method to return the full
list of clean steps when cleaning begins.

This may leave previous tenants' data on disk and available to future
tenants. Deployers should apply this patch (or upgrade to a new release
with this patch) ASAP.

Depends-On: Id15cf6cc49122b08e557e44871b31a8c0d20b55d

Change-Id: If815f81d7e668244f0d434d4e2933e8f41946107
Closes-Bug: #1517277

'}, {'created': '2015-12-02 02:31:09.000000000', 'message': "Using oslo config CONF handle for registering barbican config options

The issue is around missing barbican configuration values when
its accessed via oslo_config.cfg.CONF handle which is the mechanism
used by few openstack common components.

To address this, using oslo_config.cfg.CONF instance as base config
and registering barbican specific config options on it. If some
other plugin registers its option later (initialized on-demand),
that's okay as long as options registered does not have name conflict
with existing options. Registeration of same option multiple times
does not create issue.

Change-Id: I18d3c8850c71aa8f991e88af5ce0859a3bec2d6d
Closes-Bug: #1518510
"}, {'created': '2015-12-02 17:35:15.000000000', 'message': 'Assigning oslo config CONF once to parsed barbican CONF instance

The issue is around missing barbican configuration values when
its accessed via oslo_config.cfg.CONF handle which is the mechanism
used by few openstack common components.

To address this, assigning oslo_config.cfg.CONF instance to parsed
barbican.common.config.CONF handle at server startup only once.
Currently barbican is creating separate conf instance at
its individual plugin module and uses that in their logic. cfg.CONF
instance is primarily used by openstack common components/libs so
there is no need to keep re-assigning cfg.CONF instance at every
plugin module usage.

commit_message:
Assigning oslo config CONF once to parsed barbican CONF instance

The issue is around missing barbican configuration values when
its accessed via oslo_config.cfg.CONF handle which is the mechanism
used by few openstack common components.

To address this, assigning oslo_config.cfg.CONF instance to parsed
barbican.common.config.CONF handle at server startup only once.
Currently barbican is creating separate conf instance at
its individual plugin module and uses that in their logic. cfg.CONF
instance is primarily used by openstack common components/libs so
there is no need to keep re-assigning cfg.CONF instance at every
plugin module usage.

Change-Id: I18d3c8850c71aa8f991e88af5ce0859a3bec2d6d
Closes-Bug: #1518510

Un-pin the amphora-agent version

In the dependent patch we pinned the amphora-agent to pull the patch set
version so that scenario tests will pass.  This patch removes that pin.

commit_message:
Replaces __builtin__ with six.moves.builtins

__builtin__ does not exist in Python 3. Replacing it with
six.moves.builtins will ensure compatibility with both Python 2.7
and Python 3.4.

Removes unit tests from tests-py3.txt blacklist.

Partially implements blueprint: nova-python3-mitaka

Change-Id: I07b905df6b107ca45fd6d0e589f89bd5ac5f1830

commit_message:
Converting nova.virt.hyperv to py3

Adds changes needed to enable Python 3 unit tests in
the nova.virt.hyperv module.

Co-Authored-By: Alessandro Pilotti <apilotti@cloudbasesolutions.com>
Co-Authored-By: Lucian Petrut <lpetrut@cloudbasesolutions.com>

Partially implements blueprint: nova-python3-mitaka

Change-Id: Iaadec4e4c98be7ae428ec8228ffd6033a16ebb95

commit_message:
Validate connection limit for LBaaS

Currently, LBaaS V1 vip's connection_limit and LBaaS V2 listeners'
connection_limit can be set to a value less than -1.

This patch add a validation for V1 vip's and V2 listeners'
connection_limit resource. Setting value less than -1 is not allowed.

Closes-Bug: #1520138
Change-Id: I9332cfeda89b87dfda9cd16dcc8b1d78b6e1dc41

commit_message:
lbaasv2: validate tenant-id is non-empty in api

Lbaasv2 is not validating if the tenant-id passed in api is non-empty.
Because of this, drivers behavior is not same for the api for empty tenant-id.
To avoid this, we will validate tenant-id is non-empty at plugin.

Closes-bug: #1451621
Change-Id: I9d74a8bd9881dcff0e8d880624da9a48463aa31a

commit_message:
Put py34 first in the env order of tox

To solve the problem of "db type could not be determined" on py34 we
have to run first the py34 env to, then, run py27. This patch puts py34
first on the tox.ini list of envs to avoid this problem to happen.

Change-Id: I36ec1829229081b6bc935ecc0d27836c8699a753
Closes-Bug: #1489059

commit_message:
Reboot if master node was reinstalled

If master node is reinstalled, the bootstraped node
has outdated MCollective config and as a result it
can not be used in any deployment, but is registered as
available in Fuel. This change fixes that by making
the agent monitor master node UID and reboot itself if
the UID has changed.

Change-Id: Iacb5eca57e339f973f676712766cb613a80f393e
Closes-Bug: #1431386

commit_message:
Add /api/master_node_uid endpoint

To fix the bug linked below we need an endpoint in Nailgun
which will help fuel-nailgun-agent detect if master node
was reinstalled. This CR adds endpoint exposing master node
UID which is unique for any Fuel installation. Now
fuel-nailgun-agent can monitor that endpoint and consider
master node to be reinstalled if the UID changes.

Related-Bug: #1431386
Change-Id: I519e52542b089b13ef287256c172ababb7a362ba

A small example of how to test the CORS implementation with gabbi.

To get this to work the gabbi ConfigFixture needs to set a custom
api_paste_config to gabbi_paste.ini and called load_app instead of
setup_app to start the WSGI application. This causes the
oslo_middleware.cors middleware to be loaded, but not the
keystonemiddleware (which we do not want for these tests).

Unfortunately there's no convenient hook to load the app with a
custom set of middleware without a custom config file. Furthermore
it is challenging to override the config read by the oslo_middleware
from code instead of config. Thus we have the custom config file.

Change-Id: Id44564011f3b3fc7ed802836d61fc487dcdb60c8

commit_message:
Add simple CORS middleware gabbi tests

A small example of how to test the CORS implementation with gabbi.

To get this to work the gabbi ConfigFixture needs to set a custom
api_paste_config to gabbi_paste.ini and call load_app instead of
setup_app to start the WSGI application. This causes the
oslo_middleware.cors middleware to be loaded, but not the
keystonemiddleware (which we do not want for these tests).

Unfortunately there's no convenient hook to load the app with a
custom set of middleware without a custom config file. Furthermore
it is challenging to override the config read by the oslo_middleware
from code instead of config. Thus we have the custom config file.

Change-Id: Id44564011f3b3fc7ed802836d61fc487dcdb60c8

commit_message:
Removes wrong extra argument from vmutils method

A previous commit removed unused arguments from the methods
_set_vm_vcpus and set_vm_memory, but it wasn't removed from
create_vm.

commit_message:
Skip bindings with agent_id=None

To avoid having extra L3HARouterAgentPortBinding with l3_agent as None,
operation of setting l3_agent should be atomic.
For this purpose, transaction was added in methods
create_ha_port_and_bind and _bind_ha_router_to_agents in change
Iaad82fe522cfd70061daecf411c924fdc11b7e41

In case if router was just created and l3 agent was not scheduled yet,
so l3_agent_id is None, l3-agent-list-hosting-router <router> will fail.
This change makes it work by skipping binding with agent_id=None.

Partial-bug: #1499647

Change-Id: I1aaf4b651f738febc26b0e1105aeabe066bca2a0
(cherry picked from commit 0b8f9d0948cdb429c4b67ba138640ae515ffa1b2)

commit_message:
Correct unwatch_log to support python <= 2.7.5

Currently unwatch_log[1] uses WatchedFileHandler.delay attribute to
build a FileHandler instance from a WatchedFileHandler instance but
this attribute doesn't exist before 2.7.6.

This change removes WatchedFileHandler.delay usage and uses default
FileHandler delay (it also ensures we open immediately the log file).

[1] neutron.agent.linux.daemon

Closes-Bug: #1520271
Change-Id: I70a156c4aeeda8a3adcc1036d670732c21ffa335
(cherry picked from commit eadd68f1774e4b9c0b11d361d52f761e4588a244)

commit_message:
Remove HTTPRequestEntityTooLarge usage in test

check_img_metadata_properties_quota raises HTTPBadRequest,
it will not raise HTTPRequestEntityTooLarge
Also, updated some comments for metadata validation to
remove confusion for v2/v2.1 difference.

Change-Id: Id4fcb1c2e56d45a05d043b5fa8fe5f3e38a9d230

commit_message:
Adds HyperVSecurityGroupsDriver parent class

Adds FirewallDriver as the HyperVSecurityGroupsDriver's parent,
in order to ensure that the driver has the expected interface.

Related-Bug: #1520054

Change-Id: Ie9f5beea4a333bca879db5108b185cd80d9ab991

commit_message:
Provide detailed information on architecture

Added new global architecture diagram using Dia tool
and a more detailed description of each component.
Exported this diagram in SVG format.
The source code of the diagram is stored in
/doc/images_src/ folder.
Moved also the architecture.rst file from the /dev
folder to the root folder of the Watcher doc.

Change-Id: I74379390178673dcb6a043967b31e38ca9560bb3

[{'created': '2015-12-04 14:59:03.000000000', 'message': "Change the client imports to stop shadowing

Because sometimes the easter bunny wants to kill you, we have been
importing the client library contructor modules with a name that is
identical to the proprety we set on the class to provide the client
object. That is bad practice in any circumstance.

Since we only use those things in one and only one place, don't bother
coming up with a better alias for them - just import the module path
itself directly. Explcit good.

Change-Id: Ib0d7e616df1304277b4b9936a64793bcba8787e3
"}]
commit_message:
Change the client imports to stop shadowing

Because sometimes the easter bunny wants to kill you, we have been
importing the client library contructor modules with a name that is
identical to the proprety we set on the class to provide the client
object. That is bad practice in any circumstance.

Since we only use those things in one and only one place, don't bother
coming up with a better alias for them - just import the module path
itself directly. Explcit good.

Change-Id: Ib0d7e616df1304277b4b9936a64793bcba8787e3

To solve the problem of "db type could not be determined" on py34 we
have to run first the py34 env, then, run py27.  This patch puts py34

Change-Id: I31857b82f30b495a77d77a9df70ee31487a906b7
Closes-Bug: #1489059
'}]
commit_message:
Put py34 first in the env order of tox

To solve the problem of "db type could not be determined" on py34 we
have to run first the py34 env, then, run py27.  This patch puts py34
first on the tox.ini list of envs to avoid this problem to happen.

Change-Id: I31857b82f30b495a77d77a9df70ee31487a906b7
Closes-Bug: #1489059

commit_message:
Cache the ImageManagementService object

The mentioned object is being queried every time an operation
is performed on a VHD/VHDX. Caching the object will result in
a better performance.

Change-Id: I4e50f1b31dfa2c72188132b23ec3d5577b8a0305

commit_message:
Cleanup orphaned code from ceph backup driver

The method _num_backup_snaps was not being called anywhere in the source.
This removes the unused call from the driver.

Change-Id: Ib094edff6c26a21177405a988f132c3c6c8c9646

Having no upper bounds in requirements.txt is just wrong - pip will install the latest versions of required modules, and the code can hardly support them.'}, {'account_id': 13194, 'date': '2015-12-03 06:44:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 20:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 8777, 'date': '2015-12-03 10:27:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 20:

Alexei, commit message have a string with : Is NOT compatible with CentOS6 master node. This change request will be merged only with the  centos7'}, {'account_id': 13194, 'date': '2015-12-03 11:28:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 20:

@Roman:

nailgun works just fine with a set of modules specified in the current version of requirements.txt. All those modules support both python 2.6 and python 2.7. This patch introduces artificial incompatibility and breaks tests in a non-deterministic manner (including those using python 2.7). Specifically, after a new backwards incompatible version of some module (say, networkX) will published on PyPi, the tests will fail due to missing upper bounds.

"Not only it's not right, it's not even wrong"'}, {'account_id': 13895, 'date': '2015-12-03 17:02:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 20:

We manage bounds in repository layer. 
Why do we must bother about pip? We are ok to use pip for tests but developers should maintain test-requirements.txt on its' own. All other cases should use packages we provide and not pip or other sources of code."}, {'account_id': 7613, 'date': '2015-12-03 17:33:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 20:

@Alexey, please use test-requirements for tests.'}, {'account_id': 13194, 'date': '2015-12-04 06:23:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 20:

@Artem,

> We are ok to use pip for tests but developers should maintain test-requirements.txt on its' own

The current CI does use pip for tests, and making patch compatible with CI is a job of the author of this patch. The patch does not provide neither upper bounds in {test-,}requirements.txt, nor other means to run tests on fuel CI. Therefore the patch is wrong and should not be merged."}, {'account_id': 13194, 'date': '2015-12-04 06:34:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 20:

@Artem,

> All other cases should use packages we provide and not pip or other sources of code.

I think such an artificial restriction is absolutely unacceptable for an open source project (although I prefer to use the native package managers for installing software).

Also "use the packages we provide" (breaking requirements.txt on purpose) kind of contradicts to "zero vendor lock-in".

"If it ain't broke, don't fix it."'}, {'account_id': 10391, 'date': '2015-12-04 09:22:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 20: Code-Review+2

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 13895, 'date': '2015-12-04 09:39:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 20: Code-Review+1

requirements for tests should be tracked in test-requirements.txt. 
For production we use packages we recompile and carefully  polish according to global-requirement list. This workflow is smooth and not a subject to change. 
If patch breaks tests but not prod it's time to tune tests. This patch won't break production so please remove minus and prepare a correct test-requirements.txt if you need."}, {'account_id': 9558, 'date': '2015-12-04 09:46:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 20: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 8749, 'date': '2015-12-04 14:37:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 20: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

We are dropping support for python2.6'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-12-04 14:37:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 20: -Verified

commit_message:
Update requirements to stable/liberty

Update requirements in requirements.txt file.

Require the following modules only if python2.6:
* argparse
* ordereddict

Is NOT compatible with CentOS6 master node.

Use new oslo import notation.

Change-Id: Ib6a5be6ad784339ba4ee2f69a94a400ab8d79dfe
Blueprint: master-on-centos7

commit_message:
Adjusting commonly failing tasks

This patch takes two commonly failing tasks and configures them to be fixed
if a variable is toggled on. This is needed for gate checks to pass for
ansible-functional runs.

Closes-bug: 1521233

Change-Id: I4f54ef7af30d530f781d60ce232cc6aacda81ce4

db: prepare scripts for subproject db tables

This patch prepares related files for introducing independent sub project
tables. This is preparation for networking-odl overhaul which will
introduce new db tables.

Change-Id: I4af931f5c3acf2e12081879669f9420426d074bb

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-01 14:53:29.000000000', 'message': 'Initial support for installation of ironic-inspector

This review adds the ironic-inspector as a component that can be
opted to be installed by the user.  Note, this is moderately useless
without shade support and modules to assist the users to leverage
this workflow.

If a user wishes to utilize at this time before those items exist
then they will have to move nodes in available state back to
manageable state, and then invoke the inspect state which will
return them to manageable state once done.

Change-Id: I7b4ff92fa27578a9a7b0f25fc6e8658c3f2700aa
implements: blueprint bifrost-inspector-support

commit_message:
Initial support for installation of ironic-inspector

This review adds the ironic-inspector as a component that can be
opted to be installed by the user.  Note, this is moderately useless
without shade support and modules to assist the users to leverage
this workflow.

If a user wishes to utilize at this time before those items exist
then they will have to move nodes in available state back to
manageable state, and then invoke the inspect state which will
return them to manageable state once done.

Change-Id: I7b4ff92fa27578a9a7b0f25fc6e8658c3f2700aa
implements: blueprint bifrost-inspector-support
Depends-On: I27caa1122a72ac655958b7a6aa14b7566964f998

The patch looks good.

But I have a "philosophical" question: if, later, net associations are given attributes (or router associations, assuming they adopt the proposed behavior that create an association again would return the previously created associations), then we may have the following:
- create the association
- change the attribute to a non default value
- ...
- create the association again, expect it to be created with the default values for the attributes
- .. previous association is returned, with the non-default value of the attributes

Somehow creating an association that already exist may be a sign that the user has a bogus workflow. This is harmless only if associations don't have attributes...

So, I'm not sure we have to 'fix' bug 1512714...'}, {'account_id': 2888, 'date': '2015-12-04 09:13:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Workflow-1

commit_message:
Raise an exception for identical associations

When a request asks for creating a network association that
already exists, we have to catch the DB exception and raise an
exception that respond an error code 400.

Change-Id: Iafcaa6b016bc5f39f5ee1d64ef7ff627efa74183
Closes-Bug: 1512714

commit_message:
Update configuration section for rabbitmq

Change ID Ie027df023e6133f3188e57b42846083f28c282bd integrated the oslo_messaging_rabbit configuration into Watcher. This commit is an update
of the Watcher configuration documentation section, to take into account
new parameters for messaging RabbitMQ broker.

Change-Id: I9aa60c7dd264b4e8535e41ae2f98083985b87b0f

commit_message:
Created a glossary to lay down Watcher terminology

As of now, we do not have a single source of truth
when it comes to the terminology describing the various components
Watcher is made of. Hence, this is an attempt to formalize it into
a single document.

Change-Id: Iffbbe9148e53c88e38297fa9e81b8b024cce4099

commit_message:
Add Workload object

The patch introduces Workload model
instead of regular dict that was used to describe
scenario configuration in TaskEngine.
As a side effect it allows to fix subtask representaion
in generated reports and other rally outputs.

Change-Id: I62148707c89f575f83da11e34d0d193e716e8249

commit_message:
Put py34 first in the env order of tox

To solve the problem of "db type could not be determined" on py34 we
have to run first the py34 env to, then, run py27. This patch puts py34
first on the tox.ini list of envs to avoid this problem to happen.

Change-Id: I0cc290e9fc13c8d61d933fe4b457008df0a29c5a
Closes-Bug: #1489059

commit_message:
Put py34 first in the env order of tox

To solve the problem of "db type could not be determined" on py34 we
have to run first the py34 env to, then, run py27. This patch puts py34
first on the tox.ini list of envs to avoid this problem to happen.

Change-Id: I6616835bc5e13b07f79be584c4306e2573a002d8
Closes-Bug: #1489059

commit_message:
Update OS::Magnum::BayModel to not require network_driver

Updating this resource with changes in Magnum to allow
not specifying the network_driver.
When no network-driver is selected for baymodel create for a
given COE, Magnum should choose the default network driver for that
COE.

Change-Id: I163ba441211f41eaf9fd49b5a9adbda62e1f33ea
Related-Bug: 1501077
Depends-On: I0735f79354bc9fdb141e7a559517268e8ab648ec

commit_message:
[config-ref] Consolidate GlusterFS docu

* Follow doc conventions for wording and formatting.
* Remove optional parameter, they are all documented in the autogenerated
  table.
* Remove duplicated content.
* Remove notes about Liberty.

commit_message:
Adding a new vnic_type for Ironic/Neutron/Nova integration

A new vnic type is added to specify baremetal ports/nics.
This fix is needed to ensure that the handshake between
Neutron and Nova works fine to accomodate Ironic setting
vnic_type to baremetal

Change-Id: I5d89da1fe4c7fe463947c32364131c4a4778f13d
Implements: blueprint ironic-networks-support

commit_message:
Do not erase some packages on cleaning fuel-centos-image

We shouldn't erase packages, since we have dependencies for
them in our containers (for example httpd, cobbler, nginx, etc)

Change-Id: Ia9a1b5ba64907f5b0ec10c7ca9b14f2d4879cfdf
Closes-bug: #1509710

commit_message:
Do not expose exceptions from requests library

Novaclient expects the requests library to always be able to get a
response back and doesn't handle other cases where it might raise
an exception even before the request is completed (e.g.
ConnectionError).

These exceptions should be captured and properly converted to some
native novaclient exception.

This was originally proposed in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/235558/
without inheriting exceptions from the requests library.  That broke the
cinder gate, which relied on the old behavior, so it was reverted in
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/239941/.

In this patch, the new exceptions inherit from the requests exceptions
to ease the downstream projects' transition to expecting novaclient
exceptions instead of requests exceptions.

Change-Id: I40a6283a42a565f812a6115e382f852ad784aa92
Co-Authored-By: Kuo-tung Kao <jelly.k@inwinstack.com>
Closes-Bug: #1406586

commit_message:
Do not mount /etc/yum.repos.d into containers

Content of /etc/yum.repos.d deleted during each container
startup procedure, which doesn't look reasonable, because if
this directory is mounted to every container all that we do
is just removing it's content several times.

Blueprint: master-on-centos7

Is NOT compatible with CentOS6 master node

Change-Id: Ib668234224685d88fc34db9071f2eb87ae50f008

commit_message:
Use LVM volume group as backend for docker

In order to improve docker container performance LVM volume
group can be used as a backend for docker containers.

Requires: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/247691

Blueprint: master-on-centos7

Is NOT compatible with CentOS6 master node

Related-Bug: #1333458

Change-Id: If66f5abf5e35e3cbb5cc1f0092104eea80c2ea80

commit_message:
Systemd units for docker containers

Make every docker container a standard systemd unit, allowing
it to be managed by standard way with systemctl.

Also add systemd support to dockercrl.

Blueprint: master-on-centos7

Breaks: nothing

Change-Id: I924534b43d083f93130d2af805609a81b302d7de

PEP-0274 introduced dict comprehensions to replace dict constructor
with a sequence of length-2 sequences, these are benefits copied
from [1]:
  The dictionary constructor approach has two distinct disadvantages
  from the proposed syntax though.  First, it isn't as legible as a
  dict comprehension.  Second, it forces the programmer to create an
  in-core list object first, which could be expensive.

performance[3].
Note: This commit doesn't handle dict constructor with kwagrs.
This commit also adds a hacking rule.

commit_message:
Performance: leverage dict comprehension in PEP-0274

PEP-0274 introduced dict comprehensions to replace dict constructor
with a sequence of length-2 sequences, these are benefits copied
from [1]:
  The dictionary constructor approach has two distinct disadvantages
  from the proposed syntax though.  First, it isn't as legible as a
  dict comprehension.  Second, it forces the programmer to create an
  in-core list object first, which could be expensive.
Magnum does not support python 2.6, we can leverage this.
There is deep dive about PEP-0274[2] and basic tests about
performance[3].
Note: This commit doesn't handle dict constructor with kwagrs.
This commit also adds a hacking rule.

[1]http://legacy.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0274/
[2]http://doughellmann.com/2012/11/12/the-performance-impact-of-using
-dict-instead-of-in-cpython-2-7-2.html
[3]http://paste.openstack.org/show/480757/

Change-Id: I61992fa428d6760449afe3754b02506336e8b421

commit_message:
Swarm: Add swarm master HA support

Add --replication and --advertise to swarm master to support swarm HA.
After this patch, user can start more than 1 swarm master.

Refer docs: https://docs.docker.com/swarm/multi-manager-setup/

Partially implements: blueprint swarm-high-availability
Change-Id: I3b6c1ad64598541d055178a54f1507af6882c736

commit_message:
Move API module 'share_instances' under v2 dir

Share instances API has min version as 2.3 and considered as v2-only.
But now it is stored under v1 dir for no reason.
Move it to proper dir and remove from v1 router because it could not
be used using v1 API anyway.

Change-Id: I1e3c306b31235cd422ac339df56147439a7bbace
Closes-Bug: #1521999

commit_message:
fix error in alembic when upgrade postgresql

ALTER TYPE ... ADD cannot run inside a transaction block,
therefore we use another way to update it.

Change-Id: I8c6f62b7642917a2ea1bc0280e41261797aca172
Closes-Bug: #1520777

i don't want to look into logic of pecan but basically it expects the special methods to be non-static. if you make it static, it'll save you and continue working but it will tell you that you're using it wrong.

i think it's easier to just play along with what pecan expects.

_lookup routing in pecan is expected to be an object method. we
incorrectly set it to static which throws a few warnings. this patch

commit_message:
fix pecan _lookup usage

_lookup routing in pecan is expected to be an object method. we
incorrectly set it to static which throws a few warnings. this patch
fixes it.

Closes-Bug: #1521283
Change-Id: I0911cbe830eef84af613e08dc9495109d27a1646

commit_message:
fix expunge_metrics method

expunge_metrics method does not work properly. it uses list_metrics
from indexer to get metrics with status == 'delete'. this makes sense
but list_metrics itself is hardcoded to always search for 'active'
status. because of that, the query will always be look for status ==
'active' and status == 'delete' which can't happen so it never finds
any match.

Change-Id: I318fa5b4642a187776dce23ee9a933a5f852c4f8

commit_message:
Adhere python package requirements to Liberty global-requirements

What was done:
* versions of python packages that are requirements for the project
  changed to those from Liberty release;
* custom BaseRestController class changed to correlate with
  corresponding code of used pecan package version;
* fixed code of the orm models that become broken after installing
  SQLAlchemy package of different version

Blueprint: master-on-centos7

Is NOT compatible with CentOS6 master node

Related-Bug: #1516621

Change-Id: I9f5e600a0189d0d9fc0ae5b154254dc3a32a86c1

commit_message:
Adding indications of results after delete operations

Delete operations didn't provide any information if they
were completed succesfully, but now they do. Also few logs
were fixed.

Partially implements: blueprint cli-as-openstackclient-plugin

Change-Id: Id36af021e701b0aefaf101a07354fe11881c1f31

commit_message:
storage: retry to delete metric on failure

Currently, if a deletion fails from the storage engine, the metric is
still expunged from the indexer, meaning metricd will not retry to
delete it.

Let's make it retry by not expunging the metric from the indexer.

commit_message:
[Verify] `rally verify install/reinstall` with --no-tempest-venv

The `rally verify start` command can accept the --system-wide-install flag.
It is intended to provide a possibility to use the local environment instead
of Tempest virtual environment. The flag has a strange name, and it was decided
to use --no-tempest-venv for the `rally verify install/reinstall` commands
instead of --system-wide-install. The next patch will be dedicated to rename
--system-wide-install into --no-tempest-venv that is more logical.

In addition:
1. Some doc strings were changed to keep consistency between them;

2. Some doc strings were changed to allow users to better understand
for what options are.

3. The is_installed() method was changed to fix the following issue:
this method didn't work correctly when the --no-tempest-venv flag was passed
to `rally verify install` because it always checked existance of .venv directory.

Change-Id: I5541ac4b417152eb15b1f6277efa06c9879b4180

commit_message:
Delete python bytecode before every test run

Bring over the cleaning line from run_tests.sh for the pyc files to
all the tox runs.

This should eliminate the need to clean -x -i to kill pyc files in
your local directory to get tests to pass.

Change-Id: Ib5f4c54eae9810d7806262efd71736f2626a2176
Closes-Bug: #1368661

commit_message:
Delete python bytecode before every test run

Bring over the cleaning line from run_tests.sh for the pyc files to
all the tox runs.

This should eliminate the need to clean -x -i to kill pyc files in
your local directory to get tests to pass.

Change-Id: Ifc8df1634336fdfd298c353ad808c77f48b87b68
Closes-Bug: #1368661

commit_message:
Ensure fuel-client spec compatibility with CentOS 7

Update RPM spec to be compatible with OpenStack Liberty dependencies

Includes 'Allign requirements to Liberty'

  In order to work properly in the same environment with Liberty
  release of OpenStack, Fuel Client must follow Global Requirements
  not only by version but also by order.

Closes-bug: #1499659

Blueprint: master-on-centos7

Is NOT compatible with CentOS6 master node

Co-Authored-By: Dmitry Teselkin <dteselkin@mirantis.com>

Change-Id: Id015f22ea931e1a1e4f5dd7d6058489ba21a0808

commit_message:
Delete python bytecode before every test run

Bring over the cleaning line from run_tests.sh for the pyc files to
all the tox runs.

This should eliminate the need to clean -x -i to kill pyc files in
your local directory to get tests to pass.

Change-Id: Id236061c60ed5558459ef67752e0f504c5818b5c

commit_message:
Correct reset_state_on_error() handling

The change Ic948c2fe5baf23c9c4ced33060f672ca9c278a19 aim
to prevent the stacks hanging in IN_PROGRESS, but the code
is incorrect, this patch fix them.

Closes-Bug: #1521881
Related-Bug: #1492433
(cherry picked from commit 63141b20bcb5fe0b7941a6d8578936e42c485242)

Conflicts:
	heat/tests/test_stack.py
Change-Id: I0e9655b5a931452d810c38b7ddf6a2ce742bb7ed

[{'created': '2015-12-03 11:35:56.000000000', 'message': "HOT outputs were merged

This commit does dot HOT template outputs (for Heat.HOT/1.0 format)
the same that was previously done for the inputs. Instead of generating
MuranoPL property per each output now all outputs are put into a
single 'templateOutputs' property. This allows to eliminate the constraints
on output names, not to have collisions with input names and remain
consistent with previous changes.

Change-Id: Ibbd0a2f410c55385cd3cb9e85ea135a36460afe7
Closes-Bug: #1520954
"}]
commit_message:
HOT outputs were merged

This commit does dot HOT template outputs (for Heat.HOT/1.0 format)
the same that was previously done for the inputs. Instead of generating
MuranoPL property per each output now all outputs are put into a
single 'templateOutputs' property. This allows to eliminate the constraints
on output names, not to have collisions with input names and remain
consistent with previous changes.

Change-Id: Ibbd0a2f410c55385cd3cb9e85ea135a36460afe7
Closes-Bug: #1520954

commit_message:
Fix ISO build process for CentOS7

Existing ISO build scripts can't build CentOS7 based
ISO due to changes in package names, files, and so on.

This review fixes issue have been found, and introduces
several minor improvements.

Blueprint: master-on-centos7

Breaks: centos6

Co-Authored-By: Ivan Suzdal <isuzdal@mirantis.com>

Change-Id: I830ff03aa1051f14f2bdafb16cca1979d38e9ad5

commit_message:
Raise EntityNotFound in get_resource_info()

Rather than return None when doing get_resource_info() on resource types
that don't exist, raise an EntityNotFound exception. We can then catch that
and turn it into StackValidationFailed where appropriate, but we don't make
assumptions about where the code is being called from at the point where we
raise the exception.

Change-Id: Idf6f837befea8ccb10fdaf9196490da3dd5be1fb
Related-Bug: #1447194
Related-Bug: #1518458

commit_message:
Fix mock nbd block devices

NBD client creates a number of empty devices like /dev/nbd0..15
To fix the issue, before processing a partition script checks if
that partition was present in lsblk output.

Change-Id: I118c36a78e4661f82d4c11209ca98dca0fb2716a
Closes-Bug: #1510851
(cherry-picked from commit 10efc0f9a1166085a51d75f7fdb67b9e97ab7812)
