- noop http://logs.openstack.org/37/247537/24/check/noop/5262b08/ : SUCCESS'}, {'account_id': 14027, 'date': '2015-11-27 07:43:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 24: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

I left two inline comments, but of course these questions are about all the containers doing setup/configuration in separate scripts, or even outside of the process of building Docker image.

My general question - what's the purpose of this approach? We're losing the benefit of layered containers by doing things like that. These setup.sh scripts are, well, just bash scripts installing packages and running Puppet manifests. Is there any reason why we cannot run these commands in Dockerfiles?

I'm not active in Fuel development, so please point me if there was some discussion about this implementation which I missed."}, {'account_id': 7562, 'date': '2015-11-27 11:55:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 24:

The main idea of such separation is that CentOS7 containers perform service management actions using 'systemctl' command, which, indeed, requires systemd daemon running. It can't be started from shell script and put onto background, so the only way is to use it as PID1 process (the one that defined in CMD docker command). That's why we move all setup actions from Dockerfile to setup.sh, and modified a bit start.sh.

Another advantage here is that Dockerfile now much easier to read, and so setup.sh / start.sh.

As for having both setup.sh and start.sh - they exists because they run on different phases - setup.sh runs once during container build, and start.sh runs every time container starts, mainly to re-apply configuration changes."}, {'account_id': 14027, 'date': '2015-11-27 12:45:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 24:

Are you sure that there is no way to not run daemons during Puppet run? I'd try to do only "systemctl enable" in Puppet manifests, without "systemctl start". Then the daemons will just run after starting container.

I don't see any benefits in terms of readability when using separate start.sh scripts. Doing the same in Dockerfile looks almost the same, except all the "RUN" statements before command.'}, {'account_id': 14027, 'date': '2015-11-27 12:45:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 24:

Sorry, I meant setup.sh scripts of course.'}, {'account_id': 14027, 'date': '2015-11-27 13:40:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 24:

One other thing - IMO the approach with applying Puppet after build isn't good. If someone wants to change some installation things in already existing Docker container, why not just rebuild it and provide a new image?"}, {'account_id': 7562, 'date': '2015-11-27 13:49:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 24:

The problem is that we can't fix all the puppet manifests because some of them came from upstream.

systemd daemon can't be started just by pupping it into background, we've already tryied.

Applying puppet manifests after build is beyond of scope of this CR - it's architechtural thing, we can't change it here."}, {'account_id': 11090, 'date': '2015-11-27 14:31:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 24: Code-Review-2

I do not see any details about systemd in specification'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-27 15:22:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 24: Verified-1

[{'created': '2015-11-19 14:17:20.000000000', 'message': "Update docker containers for CentOS7

In order to migrate docker containers to CentOS7 the following
fixes and improvements were made:

* systemd service is a PID 1 service in each container instead
  of 'start.sh'
* 'start.sh' script converted to systemd service and started
  automatically every time a container is launched
* Dockerfiles simplified by removing all setup stuff to
  separate 'setup.sh' file which should be launched explicitely
  during container preparation phase

Change-Id: I5f51f473a6fa783c0a85985a5bf0412b30bcb1c2

commit_message:
Update docker containers for CentOS7

In order to migrate docker containers to CentOS7 the following
fixes and improvements were made:

* systemd service is a PID 1 service in each container instead
  of 'start.sh'
* 'start.sh' script converted to systemd service and started
  automatically every time a container is launched
* Dockerfiles simplified by removing all setup stuff to
  separate 'setup.sh' file which should be launched explicitely
  during container preparation phase

Blueprint: master-on-centos7

Is NOT compatible with CentOS6 master node

Co-Authored-By: Ivan Suzdal <isuzdal@mirantis.com>

Change-Id: I5f51f473a6fa783c0a85985a5bf0412b30bcb1c2

commit_message:
Remove requirements versions in ruby spec

Requirements should be updated to support packages versions
available in CentOS7, or removed at all, as they comes from
packages anyway.

Blueprint: master-on-centos7

Is NOT compatible with CentOS6

commit_message:
Update astute package

Add systemd unit file for astute

Add sysconfig file for astute with systemd

Upgrade spec file to support CentOS7

Blueprint: master-on-centos7

Is NOT compatible with centos 6 because in our build cases yum-builddep on ubuntu doesn't reveal rhel macros

Change-Id: Iefd9c574499a4f0022f8bbef6dc64fa04d4d2a7a

commit_message:
Fix CentOS7 based slave bootstrap

After upgrade to CentOS7 on master node bootstrap image was upgraded too,
because they use the same package base.

This commit adds fixes and minor improvements for CentOS7-based
 bootstrap:
* nailgun-agent runs only from cron
* mcollectived is a systemd unit
* setup-bootdev splitted to a regualar shell script and systemd unit
  that uses that script
* send2syslog is a systemd unit

Blueprint: master-on-centos7

Is NOT compatible with CentOS6 master node

Change-Id: I2f83096e7d64ebe52d63d06682e721f5d6bd645f

  supports substitution of some parameters out of the box

Bleuprint: master-on-centos7

commit_message:
CentOS7 master node bootstrap changes

Updates to bootstrap_admin_node:
* workaround for dracut setting the same IP address to
  multilple interfaces if they exist
* redirect output to log file

Update to ks.template:
* bootstrap_admin_node to be started as 'run-once' logon script
* drop script that modifies 'issues' file because it
  supports substitution of some parameters out of the box

Blueprint: master-on-centos7

Is NOT compatible with CentOS6 master node

Change-Id: I2feae7055b382adb0ec13a8744e3d9c9ddca16d8

Ihar,

unlike the recent ml2 version, the original extension
(for vmware?) was covered by a db migration thus doesn't

by overriding these method we added the functionality.

the situation for midonet is a bit complex because
we backported the extension to kilo. [1]
(i guess we should not have done it.)
we need to handle at least the following three cases of upgrade.
i gave up to handle them via db migration and decided
to handle them runtime as this patch.

- kilo w/o portsec -> master
- kilo w/o portsec -> kilo w/ portsec
- kilo w/ portsec -> master

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/198209/"}, {'account_id': 6854, 'date': '2015-11-24 05:13:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

recheck'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-24 05:54:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-networking-midonet-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/57/245657/1/check/gate-networking-midonet-pep8/a394910/ : SUCCESS in 2m 38s
- gate-networking-midonet-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/57/245657/1/check/gate-networking-midonet-docs/0ed4247//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 2m 36s
- gate-networking-midonet-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/57/245657/1/check/gate-networking-midonet-python27/87c650d/ : SUCCESS in 4m 46s
- gate-tempest-dsvm-networking-midonet-v1 http://logs.openstack.org/57/245657/1/check/gate-tempest-dsvm-networking-midonet-v1/40854b9/ : SUCCESS in 34m 19s (non-voting)
- gate-tempest-dsvm-networking-midonet-v2 http://logs.openstack.org/57/245657/1/check/gate-tempest-dsvm-networking-midonet-v2/bca562a/ : SUCCESS in 32m 57s (non-voting)'}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-11-27 11:16:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

@YAMAMOTO, ok, I think I see what you try to achieve. That said, overriding internal methods from neutron is prone to breakage. I also suspect that the same fix may be needed for other plugins, and the right place for it is neutron/master.

Am I right that this fix could as well go into neutron tree, and other plugins may be affected as well? Let's say I enable port_security extension after I created my networks and ports. Will I be hit by the same error?"}, {'account_id': 6854, 'date': '2015-11-27 13:59:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Ihar,

if a plugin implements the extension in the same way midonet does,
it likely have the same problem, yes.
i'm not aware of such a plugin though. (probably except vmware which
didn't have the problem as the db migration covers)

as commented in the code, my intention is to fix it in neutron later.
i'm not sure if it will accept this kind of fix though."}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-11-27 14:05:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

If my reading of the code is correct, and the error will indeed show up when you enable port security extension while having existing resources created before it's enabled, I believe it would be a proper fix for master AND neutron/kilo backport.

Seems like currently only ML2 drivers are covered from the error in neutron tree. So I would better fix it in neutron for all plugins instead of leaving it broken, and having each monolithic plugin to patch their code for the extension.

Comments?"}, {'account_id': 6854, 'date': '2015-11-27 14:27:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Ihar,

you are right.
do you know other plugins which have the same problem?'}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-11-27 14:40:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@YAMAMOTO, no, but I guess any monolithic plugin, like OVN, should be affected?'}, {'account_id': 6598, 'date': '2015-11-28 20:07:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Ihar, do you suggest to resolve this issue at Base level (probably DB mixin)?'}, {'account_id': 6854, 'date': '2015-11-30 03:06:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Ihar,

i think OVN doesn't have the problem as it has the extension from its day-one.

if a plugin added the extension by adding SecurityGroupDbMixin,
it can be affected."}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-11-30 16:51:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@YAMAMOTO, but what if someone uses OVS with the extension disabled? I suspect port security objects won't be created in db then? So once you enable the extension, you still get the issue, isn't it?

@Irena, yes, that would be ideal to fix it in base db classes."}, {'account_id': 6854, 'date': '2015-12-01 02:58:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Ihar,

you mean OVN or OVS?

OVS is ML2, which is a different implementation.
at a glance of OVN it doesn't seem to have a way to disable the extension.

i'm not against fixing it in the base class.
actually i plan to do it, as it's said in a REVISIT comment
in this patch.

are you suggesting to abandon this patch in preference of
a more generic fix?"}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-12-01 17:21:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Ah right, plugins may not expose options to disable extensions. Still, seems like an issue that CAN be in other plugins. I will check the patch again to see whether it's justified to block you here assuming you revisit it."}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-12-01 17:22:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

OK let's unblock your plugin. Next time we should be more cautious backporting extension enablement."}, {'account_id': 6854, 'date': '2015-12-03 07:07:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Ihar,

just FYI, not very related to this patch:

we (midonet) used to have options to flip extensions on and off
for a while. (in order to align with our supported backend versions)
it was very problematic and hard to maintain.  finally
we decided to separate our plugin into two variants
in order to avoid having such options.'}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-12-04 14:12:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-12-04 14:12:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

commit_message:
plugin_v2: Deal with the lack of portsecurity DB rows

For get methods, consider the lack of the binding row as
the API default value of network portsecurity.
(It's similar to ML2.  The reason it was necessary
for ML2 is a bit different from midonet, though.)

For update methods, create the binding row for the resource
if it isn't found.

Similar ML2 change: I73abc98d83372f6259f17680806e6541458e2077
Closes-Bug: #1507651
Change-Id: I97b128f2801b7bc5bf1ff028b7927bda068643d8
(cherry picked from commit 832aade785c685a87a46bad9ca49044e7e0114c6)
Conflicts:
        midonet/neutron/tests/unit/test_midonet_plugin_v2.py

commit_message:
Use the idempotent id and tooling from tempest-lib

The idempotent id decorator and the check-uuid script were migrated to
tempest-lib as part of tempest-lib 0.10.0. However, tempest was never
updated to use the library version of idempotent id or check-uuid.
This commit updates tempest to remove it's local copies of the
idempotent_id decorator and the check-uuid tool and use them from
tempest-lib instead.

Also, instead of updating the import of every single test module in
tempest an alias is just added to tempest.test to let all the old
imports work seamlessly. Updating the imports and removing the alias
may or may not be worth it in the future, but that will be a follow
on patch or discussion.

Change-Id: Iae3f491ada8f7b55c1fd817e033d968c2102d11e

commit_message:
Update required tosca-parser version

Recently tosca-parser version 0.3.0 was released and as part of enhancement
made, the heat-translator project requires tosca-parser 0.3.0 or higher. The
changes in heat-translator requirement.txt for changing required tosca-parser
version are failing which seems like because of mismatch with global
requirement.

Change-Id: Iab9b74fa5b1e0326f3e3124a145ebeb458d1bbd1

commit_message:
Use logging.NullHandler and move Django to requirements

- Adjust requirements with Django module
- Use logging.NullHandler in config
- mark 'test_filter_by_category' and 'test_check_option_switch_env' as
  expected failures, as they're not related to current failure

Co-Authored-By: Victor Ryzhenkin <vryzhenkin@mirantis.com>
Change-Id: I42c1f67f223173c78b0ff1c501bed017855873e0
Closes-Bug: #1522087

commit_message:
Raise proper exception in ext context middleware

Previously if request without 'HTTP-Authorization' header comes to
external context middleware it raised error code 500 Internal Server
Error instead of 401 Unauthorized.

Change-Id: I8285d24741bed5b541a4f8104422340c8594c695
Closes-Bug: #1522707

commit_message:
Delete python bytecode before every test run

Because python creates pyc files during tox runs, certain
changes in the tree, like deletes of files, or switching
branches, can create spurious errors.

Change-Id: Iaeb0ca55d88a3070501cb90c77cd389895bef74c
Closes-Bug: #1368661

commit_message:
Add reno for release notes management

Since reno is the new tool for Relnotes, we need to add it
to novaclient  and provide some Sphinx docs for Liberty and Mitaka.

Conflicts:
	test-requirements.txt

Change-Id: Ie42642a0e0037311cfa14cd8bf6b7041b62a4675
(cherry picked from commit 3e8cee01d5f3a6678cb641f81f88782f57a8c61a)

commit_message:
Update documentation regarding Ceilometer API V2

Today, the watcher Decision Engine is not relying on Ceilometer V2 API
to query the metrics necessary for the optimization algorithm.
This patchset update the documentation to use Ceilometer API with
watcher

Change-Id: I62cf0ea7b1766b00601f3dcbbbfe20b4a9567570

commit_message:
Add {posargs} to the command of testenv

This addition allows to run specified tests e.g.:

    $ tox -e py26,py27 -- octane/tests/test_util_node.py

Change-Id: I9b8ec97650c33084d198e652cc31d32cdbdedb8d

commit_message:
Remove py26 support

As of mitaka, the infra team won't have the resources available to
reasonably test py26, also the oslo team is dropping py26 support
from their libraries. since we rely on oslo for a lot of our work,
and depend on infra for our CI, we should drop py26 support too.

Change-Id: I7920b554f541c2c40a8a3145662a0eff7faadf2f
Closes-Bug: 1519510

commit_message:
Fix NO_DOMAIN handling with The Big Rename

Some various renamings of the "NO_DOMAIN" concept broke the very delicate
handling of a target which doesn't have a zone that it should. This
fixes it.

Change-Id: I86e537fb2b86196528821f15f1e12291be52ce33
Closes-Bug: 1522480

Add Designate API V2 support - part 1

This commit adds basic support for Rally > Designate V2 with the RecordSet and
Zone resources. More functionality will be added later.

Change-Id: I42456a404a8c8733103228f3b1e83215da9ae641

'}, {'created': '2015-11-03 15:36:27.000000000', 'message': "Add 'merge' functionality to SLA

Merge data from several SLA instances into a single one
so that the code

    sla1 = SLA()
    sla1.add_iteration(a)
    sla1.add_iteration(b)

    sla2 = SLA()
    sla2.add_iteration(c)
    sla2.add_iteration(d)

    sla3 = SLA()
    sla3.add_iteration(e)
    sla3.add_iteration(f)
    sla1.merge(sla2, sla3)

is equivalent to

    sla1 = SLA()
    sla1.add_iteration(a)
    sla1.add_iteration(b)
    sla1.add_iteration(c)
    sla1.add_iteration(d)
    sla1.add_iteration(e)
    sla1.add_iteration(f)

Needed for distribluted load generation.

    sla1.merge(sla2)

is equivalent to

    sla1 = SLA()
    sla1.add_iteration(a)
    sla1.add_iteration(b)
    sla1.add_iteration(c)
    sla1.add_iteration(d)

It is needed for distribluted load generation.

Change-Id: I1bf4b5a76a2729e800928ddd7306864de4612461
"}]
commit_message:
Add 'merge' functionality to SLA

Merge data from several SLA instances into a single one
so that the code

    sla1 = SLA()
    sla1.add_iteration(a)
    sla1.add_iteration(b)

    sla2 = SLA()
    sla2.add_iteration(c)
    sla2.add_iteration(d)

    sla1.merge(sla2)

is equivalent to

    sla1 = SLA()
    sla1.add_iteration(a)
    sla1.add_iteration(b)
    sla1.add_iteration(c)
    sla1.add_iteration(d)

It is needed for distribluted load generation.

Change-Id: I1bf4b5a76a2729e800928ddd7306864de4612461

commit_message:
Remove py26 support from designateclient

as of mitaka, the infra team won't have the resources available to
reasonably test py26, also the oslo team is dropping py26 support
from their libraries. sine we rely on oslo for a lot of our work,
and depend on infra for our CI, we should drop py26 support too.

Change-Id: Id322ec683643c817bef1de43519394808cc64072
Closes-Bug: #1519510

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-12-02 08:57:56.000000000', 'message': "default of kombu_missing_consumer_retry_timeout

This change the default of kombu_missing_consumer_retry_timeout

The initial value of 60 seconds, have been chosen because the default
rpc_response_timeout is 60. That means, the client doesn't wait for
its reply after rpc_response_timeout is reach, so we don't need
to retry it send it its reply more than rpc_response_timeout.

But the real intent of kombu_missing_consumer_retry_timeout is
to mitigate the side effect when the rabbitmq server(s) died/failover/restart.

So the question is more how long we expect the server(s) to come back
and all the oslo.messaging applications to reconnect.

In that case 60 seconds looks a bit high.

Also this 60 seconds have a sad side effect when we can't send the reply
when the rpc client is really gone (like nova-compute restart).
The rabbitmq connection to send the reply is hold during 60 seconds.

I propose 5 seconds because,i n case of failover or restart I expect
everything because normal in less that 5 seconds.

Change-Id: I2ec174e440eb91e950d9453a9de8b97ed5888968

commit_message:
default of kombu_missing_consumer_retry_timeout

This change the default of kombu_missing_consumer_retry_timeout

The initial value of 60 seconds, have been chosen because the default
rpc_response_timeout is 60. That means, the client doesn't wait for
its reply after rpc_response_timeout is reach, so we don't need
to retry it send it its reply more than rpc_response_timeout.

But the real intent of kombu_missing_consumer_retry_timeout is
to mitigate the side effect when the rabbitmq server(s) died/failover/restart.

So the question is more how long we expect the server(s) to come back
and all the oslo.messaging applications to reconnect.

In that case 60 seconds looks a bit high.

Also this 60 seconds have a sad side effect when we can't send the reply
when the rpc client is really gone (like nova-compute restart).
The rabbitmq connection to send the reply is hold during 60 seconds.

I propose 5 seconds because,i n case of failover or restart I expect
everything because normal in less that 5 seconds.

Change-Id: I2ec174e440eb91e950d9453a9de8b97ed5888968
